intro

  • feed stock- vaccum gas oil and heavy gas oil ie bottoms of VDU
  • gas oil- : 300-500 C
  • anything can be used a feed (naphtha, ethylene etc) not used due to commercial limits. however any unusable HC feed can be used as a FCC feedstock. ie to recover the
  • C5 in gasoline- gives vapours and is highly unadvised. there is a restrcition on the amount of C5 in gasoline, called as vapour locked indexC5 can always be sold to other industries as a raw material.
  • olefins are also a restriction (gum formation)
    -but still prefered since high ON.
  • indian fccs: diesel

THERMAL PROCESSES

thermal cracking

  • origins to 1800's
  • under thermal decomposition (high T, high P)
  • 1910, batch process -> contnious -> mixed (liq and vap phase cracking)
  • (typical unit image)
  • if it cracks nicely, no coking. but rarely happens so we need catalysts and control over the operating conditions

fixed bed cracking

  • catalyst- amophorous (before war)
  • catalyst increases the conversion and cycle time decreases but catalysts needs to be burnt out to avoid coking
  • here tho, coke was formed in a varied manner (high coke at the bottom and low at top, if movement is from bottom to top)

TCC airlift unit (moving beds)

playing around with contact time to decrease the coke formation

UOP stacked unit (find image)

  • steam added, to react any cracked C , acts as a stripping agent for all HCs.
  • in regenerator if there are unstripper HC, it burns out, which may lead to increase in the temperature. so steam flow rate becomes a control variable for reactor/regenerator temperature.
  • valve: catalyst movement.

exxon flexicracking unit (valve operated)

exxon model IV

FCC as a work horse

  • used a lot, since we dont need to be worried about the feedstock
  • but still not necessary for a refinery
  • FCC is operated in fluidized bed range. (pressure loss vs linear gas velocity)
  • pneumatic transport- loading and unloading
  • cylce oil- olefinic

main reactions in FCC

prefered choice of feedstock- paraffins (less coking, less gum formation)

  • catalyst- alumino silicated (amophorous). now molecular sieves are used

FCC block dig

basic process of FCC

  • feed brought in contact with hot catalyst
  • feed is vaporised, cracked and leaves behind coke
  • vapours and catalyst are sepearted
  • vapours flow thru a sep section
  • catalyst is regenerated

characterstics

modes of cracking

  • targetting the product specification
  • fcc residue- coke
  • carbonium and carbanium ions
  • formn of carbonium ion triggers the start of the FCC cracking reaction
  • reactions-
    - isomerisation
    - β transfer
    - H transfer
    - termination
  • reactivity order: unsub aromatic < paraffins < polymethyl aromatics < naphthenes < alkyl benzenes < olefins

things to be understood

catalyst manufacturers give the details, then scale
good grip of manner on how FCC operates, then favourable conditions
coke acts as a dampener for the reaction.
(?) high catalyst/oil ratio is unfavourable
endothermic reaction (reactor)

energy balance

in: feed, catalyst, air, stripping stream
out: reactor vapours, flue gas, misc. losses

feed temp: ~360, if less, more catalyst is carried, more coking occurs
torch oil

Delta coke

most imp variable in FCC
defined as differential between coke levels in spend and regenerated catalysts
imfluenced by- difference between catalyst weights, feedstock, unit hardware
contsant but not a fixed value
low coke is preferable

sensible heat- feed (liq feed needs to be turned into vapour)

refractory- similar to cement

Refractory material

Refractory materials are substances that can withstand high temperatures, pressure, and chemical exposure without breaking down. They are used to make protective linings for furnaces, kilns, and reactors.
examples: clay, alumina

Heat of reactions

  1. cracking: 60-80 kcal/kg
  2. combustion:

forms of delta coke

  1. catalytic

  2. cat/oil (amount of active sites on catalyst for oil to react)

  3. contaminant (metal contaminents enabling dehydrogenation activity)

    Bromine number

    bromine number" refers to the amount of bromine (in grams) that reacts with 100 grams of a sample, while a "bromine index" is the same measurement but expressed in milligrams per 100 grams of a sample

  4. additive

Note

FCC is not meant for making gases, it is specifically to produce a liquid product

reactions in FCC

  1. paraffins cracked to smaller parafins and olefins
  2. olefins cracking to smaller olefins
  3. aromatic side chain cracking
  4. naphtha cracking (thermal cracking= f(Temp, τ))=prods: c2,c3 (lenes)
  5. H transfer: napthene + olefins -> aromatic + parrafins
Read about
  1. Thermal cracking
  2. catalytic cracking
Note

mechanism of thermal and catalytic cracking are different from each other.

FCCu catalysts

  • catalyst acid sites- bronsted and lewis type

mechanism of Catalytic cracking reactions

  • Ch5+ doesnt have stable charge and the acid sites on th=e catalyst are not enought to form many carbonium ions. hence all cat. cracking reactions are carbenium ion chemistry
  • carbenium ion
  • crackimng: controlled by residence time (τ)
  • isoemrisation dominates
  • H transfer: favourable
  • dehydrogenation only proceeds if the catalyst is contaminated with Ni or V
  • coke formation- multi ring carbons

catalyst developement

  1. acid treated clay
  2. syntehetic silica (10-15% alumina)
  3. 1950s- silica (25% alumina)
  4. then to improve propylene cracking, appropriate catalyst was used to replcae existing catalysts

summary

cat cracking are predominantly catalytic, some non selective thermal cracking reactions do take place. these 2 processes proceed via chemistry
distribution of profucts clearly confirm this
cat cracking : carbenium ion intermediates

coke production factors

  1. condensation
  2. H transfer
  3. dehydrogenatio
  4. coke from CCR in feed
  5. adsorbed heavy HCs

FEED CHARACTERISATION

used catalyst-> cement manufacturing or metal reclaimer
feed factors-

  1. dependent on gasoline specifications
  2. coke
  3. sulphur (catalyst and SOx)
  4. contaminants (V, N, NI, Cu, Fe, Co) for catalysts
  5. alkalin earth and alkali metals -> formation of eutectic mixture with catalyst

parrafinic feed

  • easiest to crack
  • greatest amount of liq products
  • most gasoline and least flue gas but low RON
  • least coke yield
  • most desirable component in FCC feeds

olefinic feed

  • not preffered
  • indicate presence of of thermal oils which often polymerise to form undesirable coke or slurry and high gas yields
  • primary cat. cracking produces

naphthenes

  • saturated ring
  • desirable

aromatics

  • can end up as coke

physical props

  1. API gravity
    1. higher-> more aromatics are formed
  2. astm d1160
  3. refractive index
  4. anniline point
  5. bromine index
  6. viscocity
  7. condrason carbon
    1. 0.5-15%
    2. gives idea of thermal cracking
    3. coke potential indirect measure
  8. boling points

average boiling points

  1. molar
  2. weight
  3. volume
  4. cubic
  5. mean
